---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Newsletter from '../components/Newsletter.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Body — Body Sovereignty"
  description="The Body pillar at AfterChildren. Strength after 55, falls prevention, sleep, nutrition, medication management, the truth about supplements. The body you build in your 50s and 60s decides the next 30 years."
>
  <!-- PILLAR HERO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="pillar-hero">
      <p class="pillar-hero__eyebrow">Sovereignty 01</p>
      <h1 class="pillar-hero__title">
        Body.<br />
        <em>The foundation everything else sits on.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="pillar-hero__lede">
        The body you build between 55 and 65 decides whether you spend your 80s walking the neighborhood or staring at a ceiling. The financial plan does not work if you cannot get yourself off the floor at 75. The relationships do not work if your spouse becomes your full-time caregiver at 72. Body sovereignty is the highest-leverage investment available in the second half of life, and almost nobody treats it that way. This pillar is the section of the site where we tell you what actually moves the needle, in protocols, with no supplement-industry pressure.
      </p>
      <div class="pillar-hero__meta">
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">18</span> planned articles in this pillar</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">0</span> live now</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span>First article ships next week</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHERE TO START -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="start-panel">
      <p class="start-panel__eyebrow">Where to start</p>
      <h2 class="start-panel__title">Three things. This month. Not next year.</h2>
      <ol class="start-panel__list">
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Start strength training</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Two sessions per week, 45 minutes each, six compound exercises, progressive overload. The single intervention with the strongest mortality and disability data of anything available after 55. You have roughly 18 months in the high-leverage window. Bodyweight works. A gym is optional.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Get one diagnostic blood panel</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Comprehensive metabolic panel, lipid panel, A1C, vitamin D, B12, TSH, and a complete blood count. Most family doctors will run it on request. Cost: $0 to $200 depending on insurance. The baseline you set this year is what every health decision for the next 30 years gets measured against.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Fix sleep before anything else</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Most people over 55 are sleeping badly and have stopped noticing. Get screened for sleep apnea. Set a hard bedtime. Reduce alcohol. Sleep quality drives cognition, weight, mood, and recovery from every other intervention on this page. Without sleep, the other two do not work.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURED MANIFESTO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="featured">
      <p class="featured__eyebrow">Start here</p>
      <a href="/manifestos/you-raised-them-now-build-yourself" class="featured__card">
        <div class="featured__meta">
          <span class="featured__tag">Manifesto</span>
          <span class="featured__time">14 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="featured__title">You Raised Them. Now Build Yourself.</h2>
        <p class="featured__excerpt">The five-sovereignty framework underneath the entire site, and why Body is the foundation that everything else sits on. The single highest-return decision you can make in your 50s and 60s, with the brutal arithmetic behind it.</p>
        <span class="featured__cta">Read the essay <span class="featured__arrow">→</span></span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE SIX BODY SUB-PILLARS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="subpillars">
      <p class="subpillars__eyebrow">The six body domains</p>
      <h2 class="subpillars__title">The body sovereignty work, broken down.</h2>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">01</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Strength after 55</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Starting in your 30s, you lose roughly 1% of skeletal muscle per year. The rate accelerates after 60. By 75, the average sedentary adult has lost 30% to 40% of the muscle they had at peak. That loss does not show up as cosmetic decline. It shows up as the inability to get out of a chair without using your hands, the broken hip after a stumble, the first nursing home admission. The window to build the muscle that carries you into your 80s closes faster than most people expect. The high-leverage decade is 55 to 65. The protocol is simpler than the fitness industry wants you to believe.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Strength Training at 60: The Beginner's Protocol That Actually Works</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Six Exercises That Matter (And the 50 That Don't)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Progressive Overload for Beginners: The Logbook Method</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Home Gym vs. Commercial Gym: The Honest Comparison</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Returning to Lifting After 20 Years Off</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">02</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Falls prevention</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">One in four Americans over 65 falls each year. One in five of those falls causes serious injury — broken hip, head trauma, hospitalization. 60% of nursing home admissions trace to a single fall. Falls prevention is not a topic for your 80s. It is a topic for your 50s, because the strength, balance, and proprioception that prevent falls are built decades before they are tested. The interventions are unglamorous and almost completely ignored by mainstream health content. They work anyway.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Falls Prevention: The Highest-ROI Health Investment After 60</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Single-Leg Balance Test: What Your Score Means</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Home Modifications That Actually Prevent Falls</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Why Vision and Hearing Loss Drive Falls (And How to Stay Ahead of It)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">03</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Sleep</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Sleep quality declines steeply after 55. Most people stop noticing, because they have nothing recent to compare it to. Untreated sleep apnea, which affects an estimated 30% to 50% of adults over 60, drives heart disease, dementia risk, weight gain, depression, and accidents. Most people who have it are undiagnosed. Most who are diagnosed are not using their treatment consistently. Fixing sleep before anything else on this page is not a metaphor. Without it, the other interventions deliver a fraction of their potential return.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Sleep After 55: Why It Changes and What to Do</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Sleep Apnea: Why You Probably Have It and Why It Matters</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Alcohol After 55: The Sleep Cost Nobody Calculates</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Sleep Medications: The Drugs That Help, the Drugs That Hurt</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">04</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Nutrition</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Protein requirements increase after 50. Most people under-eat protein for the rest of their lives and lose muscle they cannot rebuild. Caloric needs decline. Most people fail to adjust and gain 1 to 2 pounds per year for two decades. Hydration mechanisms get less reliable. Most people are mildly dehydrated daily without knowing. The nutrition rules that worked at 35 do not work at 60. The corrections are not complicated. They are also not optional.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Protein Requirements After 50: The Number Most People Miss</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Nutrition for Aging: What Changes and Why</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Mediterranean Diet: Why the Evidence Is Stronger Than the Hype</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Hydration After 60: The Quiet Driver of Cognition and Falls</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">05</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Medications &amp; medical baseline</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">By 65, the average American is on four to seven prescription medications. By 75, often more. The interactions, side effects, and cognitive impacts compound. "Polypharmacy" is a known risk factor for falls, confusion, hospital admissions, and unnecessary mortality. Most patients do not have a single physician reviewing their full medication list against current evidence. Annual medication review with a pharmacist or geriatrician is the second-most-undervalued health intervention after strength training. It is also nearly free.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Annual Medication Review: The Free Intervention Nobody Does</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Statins After 70: When the Math Changes</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Blood Pressure Targets: Why the Numbers Have Changed</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Baseline Blood Panel: What to Order, What It Means</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">06</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">The truth about</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The supplement industry generated $52 billion in 2024. The peer-reviewed evidence supports a small fraction of what is sold. Most supplements aimed at the over-55 market do nothing or do harm. A handful — vitamin D in deficient populations, omega-3s in specific cases, creatine for muscle preservation, magnesium for sleep — have real evidence behind them. The rest is marketing. This sub-pillar exists to separate the signal from the $52 billion of noise, by name, by brand, by ingredient.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Supplements That Are Worth It (And the 90% That Aren't)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Creatine After 55: The Most Underused Tool</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Hormone Replacement Therapy: The Evidence, Not the Marketing</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Hearing Loss Denial: Why Most People Wait Seven Years Too Long</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Vision Changes After 55: What's Normal, What's Not</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMITMENTS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="commitments">
      <p class="commitments__eyebrow">Our body-content rules</p>
      <h2 class="commitments__title">What we promise on every health page.</h2>
      <div class="commitments__grid">
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">No supplement-industry money</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">We do not take sponsorship, advertising, or affiliate revenue from any supplement company, fitness equipment brand, or weight-loss product. When we recommend a supplement or product, it is because the evidence supports it. When we link to a brand, the affiliate relationship is disclosed at the top of the article, not buried at the bottom.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Not medical advice</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on this site are independent journalism, not medical advice. We cite the underlying research. We name our sources. We tell you when the evidence is strong and when it is not. We do not diagnose, prescribe, or replace your physician. We do, however, give you the questions to ask the physician you have.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Evidence, not anecdote</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Every recommendation traces to peer-reviewed evidence, meta-analyses, or large longitudinal cohort data. When we report an effect size, we cite the study. When the evidence is mixed, we say so. When the evidence has changed, we update the article and timestamp the revision. We do not chase headlines.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Reviewer layer (rolling out)</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on body topics will progressively carry a "Reviewed by [Name, Credential]" line as we bring on credentialed reviewers — a geriatrician for medication and clinical content, a registered dietitian for nutrition, a certified strength coach for training protocols. Until then, articles in this section are bylined by M. Holloway, the founder, or the AfterChildren Editorial Desk, and reflect independent research only.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- AFFILIATES -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="affiliates">
      <p class="affiliates__eyebrow">Affiliate disclosure</p>
      <h2 class="affiliates__title">What we link to, and what we earn.</h2>
      <p class="affiliates__intro">When we recommend a product, we link to it. When the link earns us a commission, we disclose it. We only link to products we have evaluated and believe in. We do not link to supplements, devices, or programs we would not use ourselves.</p>
      <p class="affiliates__intro affiliates__intro--secondary">As this pillar develops, the partner list below will become live affiliate links. Until then, the list documents the categories we are evaluating for inclusion. We will publish an honest review of each before any link goes live.</p>
      <div class="affiliates__list">
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Hearing aids</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Direct-to-consumer hearing aids that work without four-figure clinic markups. Under evaluation: Eargo, Jabra Enhance, Lexie.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Strength &amp; mobility equipment</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Adjustable dumbbells, suspension trainers, balance tools that hold up to daily use. Under evaluation: Bowflex SelectTech, TRX, BOSU.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Sleep technology</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">At-home sleep apnea screening, sleep trackers with real validity data. Under evaluation: WatchPAT One, Oura Ring, Garmin.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Vetted supplements</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Third-party-tested brands for the small list of supplements with real evidence: vitamin D, omega-3s, creatine, magnesium. Under evaluation: Thorne, Pure Encapsulations, NOW Foods.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Mobility &amp; aging-in-place</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Grab bars, shower chairs, raised toilet seats, fall-detection devices. Under evaluation: Moen Home Care, Stander, Apple Watch fall detection.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Vision &amp; eye health</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Direct-to-consumer progressive lenses, blue-light glasses where the evidence supports it, eye-exam scheduling. Under evaluation: Warby Parker, Felix Gray, Zenni.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA: ASK A QUESTION -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="ask">
      <h2 class="ask__title">A body question we should answer?</h2>
      <p class="ask__lede">If a Body topic is on your mind and not on the list above, note it. The most-asked questions become next month's articles. A public contact channel for reader questions is coming once the site has enough readers to make the conversation worth the inbox.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Newsletter />
</Base>

<style>
  /* =====================================
     Pillar page–specific styles
     Same system as /money for visual consistency.
     ===================================== */

  .pillar-hero {
    padding: var(--space-24) 0 var(--space-16);
